:::summary
Roman philosophy was not an original creation but a magnificent adaptation — Rome's educated elite absorbed the schools of Greek thought, particularly Stoicism and Epicureanism, and recast them in Latin for a civilization obsessed with practical virtue, public duty, and the ordering of human affairs. Figures such as [Cicero](article.html?id=cicero), Seneca, and [Marcus Aurelius](article.html?id=marcus-aurelius) produced philosophical writings of enduring power, and their ideas about natural law, reason, and human dignity flowed directly into Christian theology and, centuries later, into the American founding.
:::

