## Rome's Encounter with Greek Thought

When Rome conquered Greece militarily in the 2nd century BC, Greece conquered Rome intellectually. The educated Roman aristocracy embraced Greek philosophy with enthusiasm, sending their sons to study in Athens and importing Greek philosophers to Rome as tutors. Latin had no philosophical vocabulary; Roman thinkers had to invent it, coining dozens of Latin terms — *essentia*, *qualitas*, *moralis* — that passed into European languages and remain in use today.

Rome's philosophical temperament was intensely **practical**. The Romans were less interested in abstract metaphysics than in the questions that mattered for governing an empire and living a good life: How should a statesman conduct himself? What does reason demand of us? How do we face death with courage? The schools that thrived in Rome — above all Stoicism — were those that answered these questions directly.

## Cicero: Philosophy in Latin

**Marcus Tullius Cicero** (106–43 BC) is the towering figure of Roman intellectual life. A statesman, lawyer, and orator, Cicero was also Rome's greatest philosopher — not because he developed original doctrines, but because he translated and synthesized Greek philosophy for a Latin audience with extraordinary clarity and elegance.

:::dropdown Cicero's Major Philosophical Works
- ***De Re Publica*** (*On the Republic*) — political philosophy; the ideal Roman state; the famous "Dream of Scipio," a vision of the cosmos and the soul's immortality
- ***De Legibus*** (*On the Laws*) — natural law as the foundation of all human legislation
- ***De Finibus*** (*On Ends*) — a systematic survey of the Greek ethical schools
- ***Tusculan Disputations*** — how to face death, pain, and the passions with philosophical courage
- ***De Officiis*** (*On Duties*) — practical ethics; the duties owed by a man in public life; heavily influenced by Stoicism

*De Officiis* was one of the most widely read books in Western history, standard reading for educated men from the Renaissance through the American founding era. The Founders drew on it directly.
:::

Cicero embraced a moderate **Academic Skepticism** in epistemology — holding that certain knowledge is impossible but that we should act on the most probable opinion — while drawing heavily on Stoic ethics, especially the doctrine of **natural law**.

### Cicero and Natural Law

Cicero articulated the classical doctrine of **natural law** with unmatched clarity:

:::quote Cicero, *De Re Publica*, III.22
"True law is right reason in agreement with nature; it is of universal application, unchanging and everlasting; it summons to duty by its commands, and averts from wrongdoing by its prohibitions... It is a sin to try to alter this law, nor is it allowable to repeal any part of it, and it is impossible to abolish it entirely."
:::

This passage became foundational for Christian political thought, canonized by [Aquinas](article.html?id=aquinas) in his account of natural law, and echoed in the [Declaration of Independence](article.html?id=declaration-of-independence) — Jefferson's "Laws of Nature and of Nature's God."

## Lucretius and Epicurean Poetry

**Titus Lucretius Carus** (~99–55 BC) was Rome's great Epicurean, and his poem *De Rerum Natura* (*On the Nature of Things*) is one of the masterworks of Latin literature. Drawing on Democritus and Epicurus, Lucretius argued for a fully materialist universe of atoms and void — no divine providence, no immortal soul, no afterlife. Death is simply the dissolution of the atoms that compose us; there is nothing to fear.

Lucretius is brilliant but, from a Christian perspective, deeply mistaken. His materialism, rediscovered in the Renaissance, contributed to the skeptical currents that the Church had to engage and refute. Yet his poem's power as literature has never been in doubt.

## Roman Stoicism

Stoicism, founded in Athens, achieved its greatest literary expression in Rome. Three Roman Stoics are especially important:

### Seneca

**Lucius Annaeus Seneca** (4 BC – 65 AD) was a philosopher, playwright, and the tutor and advisor of the emperor Nero. His *Letters to Lucilius* and philosophical essays are among the most readable and searching moral writings in any language. Seneca wrote with passionate urgency about the shortness of life, the dangers of wealth and ambition, and the necessity of cultivating the inner life.

:::quote Seneca, *Letters to Lucilius*, 1.1
"Reclaim yourself — gather and save the time which till lately has been forced from you, or filched away, or has merely slipped from your hands."
:::

Seneca's death — forced by Nero to commit suicide — was witnessed by his friends as a Stoic martyrdom.

### Epictetus

**Epictetus** (~50–135 AD) was a Greek-speaking slave who became Rome's most influential Stoic teacher. His *Discourses* and *Enchiridion* (*Handbook*) radically distinguish what is "up to us" (our judgments, desires, and will) from what is not (our body, reputation, property). Freedom, on Epictetus's account, is entirely internal: the person whose will is aligned with reason and nature cannot be enslaved, no matter what happens to his body.

Epictetus's emphasis on inner freedom, the brotherhood of all rational beings under one divine Reason, and the duty to care for one's fellow human beings resonated powerfully with early Christian thought.

### Marcus Aurelius

**Marcus Aurelius** (121–180 AD) was a Roman emperor and a Stoic philosopher — the closest the ancient world came to Plato's philosopher-king. His *Meditations* are a private journal, never intended for publication, in which the emperor disciplines his own mind and soul with Stoic exercises. They remain one of the most moving documents of human moral striving.

